A landmark ruling on piracy and privacy on the internet means thousands of Australians could be getting letters threatening legally action if they illegally downloaded and shared Hollywood film Dallas Buyers Club .
But internet law experts say the company behind the letters will have a hard time following through on the threats because it is very difficult to prove who is legally responsible for the downloading .
The Federal Court ruled on Tuesday that Australian internet companies should hand over the names and residential addresses of 4,726 people who shared the film .
